dataset.title: Wisconsin Surface Water Integrated Monitoring System (SWIMS) Department of Natural Resources lake nutrient data, 1970-2011

creator.organizationName: Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources - Water Quality Bureau

abstract.para: The Wisconsin Surface Water Integrated Monitoring System (SWIMS) program is the state´s repository for water and sediment monitoring data collected for Clean Water Act work and is the source of data sharing through the federal Water Quality Exchange Network. DNR Fisheries and Water Quality Biologists use the system to locate monitoring stations, providing a gateway to final, reviewed fisheries management datasets housed at the U.S. Geological Survey. SWIMS is also the data system that citizen volunteers use to document water monitoring results for our state´s lakes, streams and wetlands. Parameters typically collected on lakes are total phosphorus, chlorophyll a and Secchi. Through the DNR Long-Term Trend monitoring program, additional parameters such as Nitrogen have been collected. Lake data in SWIMS generally goes back to the 1970s (1970s data was imported in from the EPA STORET database, where DNR laboratory results went historically). The database is updated daily.

section.title: Quality Assurance/ Quality Control of field and lab data
section.para: Blanks and duplicates are done on 10% of volunteer water chemistry sites each year. Blanks and duplicates are done on DNR Long Term Trend sites from time-to-time, but I do not know if that is systematically done. The State Laboratory of Hygiene is a quality assured lab and certified by the State of Wisconsin and follows EPA standards and protocols.

samplingDescription.para: Volunteers (who collect the majority of our state's lake data) monitor lakes at 4 times per year for water chemistry and as often as every two weeks for Secchi. DNR Staff who monitor through the long term trends program visit each of the 50+ lakes once a year, and sometimes multiple times during the summer
